{% block bodyContent %}

  {{ designExample({
    group: "components",
    item: "link-icon",
    type: "default"
  }) }}

  <h2>When to use link icons</h2>
  <p>Use link icons when a prominent text link needs a clear directional cue, such as going back or opening something externally.</p>
  <p>The canonical link icon component supports left and right icon positions so teams can keep the same underlying pattern for back links and outward links.</p>

  <h2>When not to use link icons</h2>
  <p>Do not use link icons for the primary action in a form or transactional step. Use the <a href="/design-system/components/button">Button</a> component instead.</p>
  <p>Do not add icons to ordinary inline text links just to make them look more decorative. Reserve this pattern for navigation links where the icon adds meaning, such as returning to a previous step or signposting an external destination.</p>
  <p>For back-navigation variants, do not use a link icon with <a href="/design-system/components/breadcrumbs">breadcrumb</a> navigation on the same page.</p>

  <h2>How to use link icons</h2>
  <p>Keep the text short and specific. Use a left icon for back-navigation style links and a right icon for external or forward-moving links.</p>
  <p>Choose the small size for compact inline usage and the medium size when the link needs more visual emphasis.</p>
  <p>For back-navigation patterns, make sure the text reflects the action clearly, for example "Go back" or "Change your previous answer". The icon should support the action, not replace it.</p>
  <p>If a link icon takes people back through a transaction, it should return them to the page in the state they last saw it.</p>
  <p>Consider where you place the link. Avoid putting it too close to other links or buttons where it could distract from the main task.</p>

  <h3 id="customise-link-icons">Customise link icons</h3>
  <p>The same macro can cover back-navigation, outward links and other prominent navigation links.</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Use <code>text</code> for plain labels, or <code>html</code> if the label needs trusted inline markup.</li>
    <li>Use <code>iconPosition</code> to place the icon on the left or right of the text.</li>
    <li>Use <code>iconName</code> to choose any toolkit icon. If you leave it unset, the macro uses <code>ChevronLeft</code> for left icons and <code>Launch</code> for right icons.</li>
    <li>Use <code>size</code> to switch between <code>small</code> and <code>medium</code>.</li>
    <li>Use <code>openInNewWindow</code> when the destination should open in a new tab. The macro adds the safe <code>rel</code> value for you.</li>
    <li>Use <code>iconColor</code> only when the icon needs to differ from the text colour.</li>
    <li>Use <code>classes</code> and <code>attributes</code> for integration hooks rather than creating new visual variants.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3 id="right-icon-and-medium-size">Right icon and medium size</h3>
  <p>Use a right icon when the link points outward to another destination or signals forward movement through a journey.</p>

  {{ designExample({
    group: "components",
    item: "link-icon",
    type: "right-icon"
  }) }}

  <h3 id="custom-icon-and-colour">Custom icon and colour</h3>
  <p>Choose a different icon when it adds meaning to the link, and only override the icon colour when the icon should not inherit the text colour.</p>

  {{ designExample({
    group: "components",
    item: "link-icon",
    type: "custom-icon-colour"
  }) }}

  <h3>Accessibility</h3>
  <p>Make sure the text still describes the action on its own. The icon should support the message, not replace it.</p>
  <p>If the right-icon variant opens a new tab or takes users outside the current journey, make that clear in the visible link text or surrounding context.</p>
  <p>For back-navigation variants, think about screen reader users when choosing placement. In some journeys it may work better below the primary action rather than at the very top of the page.</p>

  <h2>Research</h2>
  <p>Back-navigation guidance in this pattern comes from earlier back-link research across transactional services.</p>
  <p><a href="https://111.nhs.uk/">NHS 111 online</a> found that some users wanted to revisit and change their previous answers, so they used explicit back-navigation wording rather than relying on the icon alone.</p>
  <p>The <a href="https://digitalaccessibilitycentre.org/">Digital Accessibility Centre</a> also found that some screen reader users were confused when a back-navigation link appeared too early in the page order, so placement should be chosen intentionally.</p>

